rban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Croy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Orkney): habitational name from any of several places called Croy, for example in Inverness-shire.","Probably also Irish: shortened form of   McCroy  , which is a variant of   McRoy  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McCroy","meanings":["Irish: variant of   McRoy  ."]}]},{"name":"Jacques","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   James   and   Jacob .  In French there is no distinction between a form corresponding to <i>Jacob</i> and a form corresponding to <i>James</i>. This is a perennially popular French given name, and <i>Jacques</i> or <i>Jacques Bonhomme</i> has been used (like <i>John Bull</i> in English) as a typification of the ordinary citizen. In  Shakespeare's  time it was also used as an English name, pronounced ‘<b>jay</b>-kwez’, as in the case of the melancholy character Jacques in As You Like It. Though rarely, if ever, now used in Britain it is found in the United States."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"le","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Lewis   or respelling of   Lou  , as borne by the impresario  Lew Grade  (  1906–98 , originally  Louis Winogradsky )."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Vieux","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Edouard, Jacques, Pierre, Colette, Fernande, Georges, Germaine, Manon.","Altered form of French   Viau  .","French: from <i>vieux</i> ‘old’, probably applied as a nickname but also as a distinguishing epithet for the older of two bearers of the same personal name."],"variants":[{"name":"Viau","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Pierre, Albertine, Andre, Armand, Edouard, Francois, Gaston, Gilles, Gisele, Jean Marie, Jean-Paul.","French: variant of   Vial  . Compare   Vieau  ,   Vieu  , and   Vieux  .","History: Jacques Viau <i>dit</i> Lespérance from Clisson in Loire-Atlantique, Brittany (France), married Madeleine Plouard in Montreal, QC, in 1670. Jean Viau from Ozillac in Charente-Maritime, France, married Françoise Prévost in Montreal, QC, in 1711."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jacques II  le Vieux de Croy was born about 1288, in Airaines, Somme, Picardie, France, his father, Jacques Ier de CROY, was 27 and his mother, Marguerite d’Airaines, was 25. He had at least 2 sons with Marie de Picguigny."},"et":{"environ 1288–":"umbes 1288–Surnud","1288–Male":"1288–Surnud","1292–1367":"1292–1367","1320–1365":"1320–1365","1335–1384":"1335–1384","1263–1313":"1263–1313","1265–Female":"1265–Surnud","environ 1288":"umbes 1288","1335":"1335","1313":"1313","1367":"1367","1365":"1365","1288":"1288","1320":"1320","1265":"1265","1263":"1263","1384":"1384","1292":"1292","Brussel, België":"Brussel, Belgia","Airaines, Somme, Picardie, France":"Airaines, Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"environ 1288–":"noin 1288–Kuollut","1288–Male":"1288–Kuollut","1292–1367":"1292–1367","1320–1365":"1320–1365","1335–1384":"1335–1384","1263–1313":"1263–1313","1265–Female":"1265–Kuollut","environ 1288":"noin 1288","1